comments.body:
> because users don't see the actual command line that was ultimately used

Which is one reason why PSCX has shipped with an echoargs.exe utility for ~10 years now.  This utility should probably come with PowerShell unless we manage to clear up all the "invoking an exe with args" issues (doubtful).  Here's the complete implementation of this utility:
```csharp
using System;

namespace Pscx.Applications
{
    class EchoArgs
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            for (int i = 0; i < args.Length; i++)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Arg {0} is <{1}>", i, args[i]);
            }

            Console.WriteLine("\nCommand line:");
            Console.WriteLine(Environment.CommandLine);
            Console.WriteLine();
        }
    }
}
```
Giving:
```
68:60ms> echoargs set winrm/config/client/auth @{Basic="true"}
Arg 0 is <set>
Arg 1 is <winrm/config/client/auth>
Arg 2 is <System.Collections.Hashtable>

Command line:
"C:\Users\Keith\Documents\WindowsPowerShell\Modules\Pscx\3.2.2\Apps\EchoArgs.exe" set winrm/config/client/auth System.Collections.Hashtable
```
